    • Field Detail

      • cells

        protected final ByteBuffer[] cells
        Array of equal capacity cells, windows into the block, in block-offset order. The cell buffers are maintained in clear-ed state.

    • Constructor Detail

      • Block

        public Block(Block copy)
        Copy constructor. The new instance shares the same backing buffers. That is, content modifications in one buffer are also visible in the other.

      • Block

        public Block(ByteBuffer block,
     int cellByteWidth,
     boolean readOnlyCells)
        Creates a new instance with the given block and cellByteWidth. Nags if the block's capacity is not a multiple of the cell width.
        Parameters:
        readOnlyCells - if true, then the cells will be read-only. If the block itself is read-only, then this parameter doesn't matter: the cells will be read-only, regardless.

    • Method Detail

      • cellCount

        public final int cellCount()
        Returns the number of cells in this block.

      • cellWidth

        public final int cellWidth()
        Returns the number of bytes in each cell.

      • isReadOnly

        public final boolean isReadOnly()
        Tests whether this is a read-only instance. If read-only, the block's content cannot be modified through this instance.

      • readOnlyCells

        public final boolean readOnlyCells()
        Tests whether this instance's cells are read-only. This method can return true even if isReadOnly() returns false.

      • isDirect

        public final boolean isDirect()
        Determines whether this instance is made up of direct buffers. Either all or none of the buffers are direct.

      • buffer

        public final ByteBuffer buffer()
        Returns the backing buffer. The capacity of the returned buffer is equals to the sum of the capacities of its cells. Modifications in the returned buffer's content are visible in the cells and vice versa. The position and limit of the returned buffer is independent of those of the cells. The returned buffer is read-only, if isReadOnly() returns true. Modifications to the buffer's position and limit are ignored by this class. The contents of the returned buffer may be ordered differently than the order of this instance's cells.

      • cells

        public final ByteBuffer[] cells()
        Returns a new copy of the cells array. Each of the cells is a view on to the backing block. Modifications in any individual element's content are visible in the backing buffer() and vice versa. The position and limit of the returned cells (set to zero and capacity, resp.) are independent of any other buffer. The returned buffers are read-only, if readOnlyCells() returns true.
        See Also:
        buffer();

      • cell

        public ByteBuffer cell(int index)
        Returns a new copy of the cell at the specified index. The returned cell is a view on to the backing buffer: modifications in the returned buffer's content are visible in the backing buffer() and vice versa. The position and limit of the returned cell (set to zero and capacity, resp.) are independent of any other buffer. The returned buffer is read-only, if readOnlyCells() returns true.
        Throws:
        IndexOutOfBoundsException - if index is out of range

      • copyCellInto

        public void copyCellInto(int index,
                ByteBuffer buffer)
                  throws BufferOverflowException
        Copies the contents of the cell at the given index into the buffer. The position of the given buffer is advanced by the cell width. Invoking this method makes the instance especially unsuitable for concurrent read access.
        Throws:
        BufferOverflowException
